Q. but the feild type is User , not int , so by passing just 1 , in the post api so
how will we be getting it ?

Scenario: Field Type is User, JSON Contains Only ID

Entity:

@Entity
public class Order {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    private String product;

    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "user_id")
    private User user;
}


POST Request JSON
json

{
  "product": "Book",
  "user": { "id": 1 }
}

How Does Spring/Jackson Handle This?

(i) When you send { "user": { "id": 1 } }, Jackson (the JSON library used by Spring) tries to
create a User object and sets only its id field to 1.
(ii) The other fields of User (like name, email) are left null in this deserialized object.
(iii) Spring/JPA does NOT fetch the full User object at this point.

When you call orderRepository.save(order), JPA sees that the Order has a User object with only
the id set.
a. JPA uses the id to set the foreign key (user_id) in the order table.
b. JPA does not insert a new user; it just links the order to the existing user with id=1.

What If You Pass Only the ID (Not an Object)?

If you try to send:

{
  "product": "Book",
  "user": 1
}

This will not work by default with a User-typed field, because Jackson expects an object for
the user field, not a number.

You would get a deserialization error unless you write a custom deserializer or use a DTO.

Best Practice: Use a DTO for Simpler Input

DTO Example:

public class OrderDTO {
    private String product;
    private Long userId;
}

Controller:

@PostMapping("/orders")
public Order createOrder(@RequestBody OrderDTO orderDTO) {
    User user = userRepository.findById(orderDTO.getUserId())
        .orElseThrow(() -> new RuntimeException("User not found"));
    Order order = new Order();
    order.setProduct(orderDTO.getProduct());
    order.setUser(user);
    return orderRepository.save(order);
}

POST JSON:

{
  "product": "Book",
  "userId": 1
}

Summary Table

Field Type in Entity	      JSON Input Needed	             What Happens?
User user	                  { "user": { "id": 1 }}	     Jackson creates User with id=1,
                                                             JPA links by id
Long userId	                  { "userId": 1 }	             Jackson sets userId, you fetch
                                                             User manually


In short:

a.If your field is User, you must send an object with at least the id in the JSON.
b.Jackson will create a User with only the id set.
c.JPA will use that id to set the foreign key, linking the order to the existing user.
